---

Most disables are not random. Meta's automated systems build a behavioral baseline for every profile and flag anything that breaks sharply from it. Understand what they watch for, and you can stay well clear of the danger zone.

### What triggers a disable, and what to do instead

| Risky behavior | Do this instead |
| --- | --- |
| Low-quality or mismatched proxy | Use a residential proxy that matches the profile's history |
| Sudden IP, device, or spend changes | Keep IP, device, and spending consistent and gradual |
| Creating new BMs or Pages on aged profiles | Never create fresh BMs or Pages on aged profiles |
| Rapid mass actions (many admins or shares at once) | Add admins and share assets gradually |
| Long dormancy, then heavy usage | Log in regularly to keep the profile naturally active |
| Spammy or policy-violating content | Follow Meta's advertising policies carefully |

{% callout variant="tip" title="Consistency is everything" %}
The closer your activity matches the profile's natural history, the safer it is. Slow, steady, and predictable beats fast and erratic every time. For the full playbook, see [Security Tips](/docs/questions-bank/security-tips).
{% /callout %}
